# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: structlog
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:structlog/getting-started] If you want pretty exceptions in development (you know you do!), additionally install Rich.
[src:structlog/getting-started] The screenshot in the README and docs homepage is rendered by Rich.
[src:structlog/getting-started] On **Windows**, you also have to install Colorama if you want colorful output beside exceptions.
[src:structlog/getting-started] A lot of effort went into making *structlog* accessible without reading pages of documentation.
[src:structlog/getting-started] Please note that even in most complex logging setups the example would still look just like that thanks to Configuration.
[src:structlog/getting-started] However, this alone wouldn’t warrant its own package.
[src:structlog/getting-started] After all, there’s even a recipe on structured logging for the standard library.
[src:structlog/getting-started] The calls themselves are nice and straight to the point, however you’re repeating yourself all over the place.
[src:structlog/getting-started] It’s easy to forget to add a key-value pair in one of the incantations.
[src:structlog/getting-started] What if the parameters are introduced step by step?
[src:structlog/getting-started] And do you really want to have a logging closure in each of your views?
[src:structlog/getting-started] Suddenly your logger becomes your closure!
[src:structlog/getting-started] The last point is very clean and easy to reason about, but sometimes it’s useful to store *some* data globally.
[src:structlog/getting-started] In our example above the peer IP comes to mind.
[src:structlog/getting-started] There’s no point in extracting it in every view!
[src:structlog/getting-started] See Context Variables for more information and a more complete example.
[src:structlog/getting-started] Now that your log events are dictionaries, it’s also much easier to manipulate them than if they were plain strings.
[src:structlog/getting-started] To facilitate that, *structlog* has the concept of processor chains.
[src:structlog/getting-started] A processor is a function that receives the event dictionary along with two other arguments and returns a new event dictionary that may or may not differ from the one it got passed.
[src:structlog/getting-started] The next processor in the chain receives that returned dictionary instead of the original one.
[src:structlog/getting-started] Let’s assume you wanted to add a timestamp to every event dict.
[src:structlog/getting-started] Finally you want to have control over the actual format of your log entries.
[src:structlog/getting-started] As you may have noticed in the previous section, renderers are just processors too.
[src:structlog/getting-started] The type of the return value that is required from the renderer depends on the input that the *logger* that is wrapped by *structlog* needs.
[src:structlog/getting-started] While usually it’s a string or bytes, there’s no rule saying it *has* to be a string!
[src:structlog/getting-started] While *structlog*’s loggers are very fast and sufficient for the majority of our users, you’re not bound to them.
[src:structlog/getting-started] Instead, it’s been designed from day one to wrap your *existing* loggers and **add** *structure* and *incremental context building* to them.
[src:structlog/getting-started] The most prominent example of such an “existing logger” is certainly the logging module in the standard library.
[src:structlog/getting-started] To make this common case as simple as possible, *structlog* comes with some tools to help you.
[src:structlog/getting-started] As noted before, the fastest way to transform *structlog* into a `logging`-friendly package is calling `structlog.stdlib.recreate_defaults()`.
[src:structlog/getting-started] You can use the sync and async logging methods interchangeably within the same application.
[src:structlog/getting-started] Now you’re all set for the rest of the user’s guide and can start reading about bound loggers – the heart of *structlog*.
[src:structlog/getting-started] For a fully-fledged zero-to-hero tutorial, check out *A Comprehensive Guide to Python Logging with structlog*.
[src:structlog/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:structlog/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:structlog/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:structlog/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:structlog/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:structlog/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:structlog/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:structlog/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:structlog/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:structlog/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:structlog/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:structlog/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:structlog/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:structlog/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:structlog/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:structlog/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:structlog/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:structlog/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:structlog/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:structlog/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:structlog/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:structlog/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:structlog/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:structlog/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:structlog/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:structlog/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:structlog/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:structlog/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:structlog/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:structlog/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:structlog/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:structlog/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:structlog/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:structlog/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:structlog/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:structlog/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:structlog/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:structlog/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:structlog/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:structlog/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:structlog/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:structlog/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:structlog/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:structlog/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:structlog/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:structlog/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:structlog/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:structlog/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:structlog/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:structlog/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:structlog/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:structlog/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:structlog/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:structlog/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:structlog/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:structlog/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:structlog/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:structlog/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:structlog/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:structlog/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:structlog/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:structlog/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:structlog/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:structlog/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:structlog/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:structlog/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:structlog/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:structlog/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:structlog/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:structlog/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:structlog/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:structlog/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:structlog/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:structlog/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:structlog/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:structlog/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:structlog/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:structlog/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:structlog/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:structlog/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:structlog/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:structlog/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:structlog/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:structlog/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:structlog/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:structlog/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:structlog/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:structlog/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:structlog/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:structlog/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:structlog/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:structlog/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:structlog/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:structlog/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:structlog/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:structlog/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:structlog/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:structlog/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:structlog/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:structlog/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:structlog/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:structlog/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:structlog/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:structlog/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:structlog/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:structlog/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:structlog/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:structlog/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:structlog/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:structlog/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:structlog/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:structlog/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:structlog/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:structlog/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:structlog/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:structlog/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:structlog/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:structlog/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:structlog/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:structlog/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:structlog/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:structlog/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:structlog/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:structlog/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:structlog/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:structlog/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:structlog/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:structlog/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:structlog/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:structlog/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:structlog/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:structlog/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:structlog/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:structlog/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:structlog/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:structlog/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:structlog/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:structlog/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:structlog/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:structlog/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:structlog/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:structlog/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:structlog/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:structlog/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:structlog/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:structlog/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:structlog/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:structlog/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:structlog/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:structlog/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:structlog/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:structlog/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:structlog/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:structlog/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:structlog/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:structlog/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:structlog/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:structlog/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:structlog/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:structlog/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:structlog/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:structlog/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:structlog/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:structlog/why] Structured logging means that you don’t write hard-to-parse and hard-to-keep-consistent prose in your log entries.
[src:structlog/why] Instead, you log *events* that happen in a *context* of key-value pairs.
[src:structlog/why] More general advice about production-grade logging can be found in the later chapter on Logging Best Practices.
[src:structlog/why] Each log entry is a meaningful dictionary instead of an opaque string now!
[src:structlog/why] That said, *structlog* is not taking anything away from you.
[src:structlog/why] You can also bind key-value pairs to context variables that look global, but are local to your thread or *asyncio* context – which usually means your web request.
[src:structlog/why] Each log entry goes through a processor pipeline that is just a chain of functions that receive a dictionary and return a new dictionary that gets fed into the next function.
[src:structlog/why] Internally, formatters are processors whose return value (usually a string) is passed into loggers that are responsible for the output of your message.
[src:structlog/why] *structlog* comes with multiple useful formatters out-of-the-box.
